      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i'm stuck on this circuit problem. i have a series circuit with a 12V AC source at 60Hz. there's a 100 ohm resistor and an inductor with an inductive reactance of 50 ohms. how do i find the total impedance and the current? thanks",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "In a series circuit, you find the total impedance, $Z$, by combining the resistance ($R$) and the inductive reactance ($X_L$) using the Pythagorean theorem. You can calculate this by squaring the resistance and the reactance, adding them together, and then taking the square root of the result.\n\nSo, for your problem, the total impedance is:\n\n$$Z = \\sqrt{R^2 + X_L^2}$$\n\nPlugging in your values: $Z = \\sqrt{100^2 + 50^2}$\n\n$$Z = \\sqrt{10000 + 2500}$$\n\n$$Z = \\sqrt{12500}$$\n\n$$Z \\approx 111.8 \\text{ ohms}$$\n\nNow that you have the total impedance, you can find the current ($I$) using Ohm's Law for AC circuits, which is the voltage divided by the impedance:\n\n$$I = \\frac{V}{Z}$$\n\n$$I = \\frac{12\\text{V}}{111.8\\ \\Omega}$$\n\n$$I \\approx 0.107 \\text{ Amperes}$$",
      "source": "target",
